node.text:
Powerful words.💪🏽 ⤵️

#Repost: @kyliegrimes7 

𝚃𝚑𝚎 𝙿𝚊𝚛𝚊𝚕𝚢𝚖𝚙𝚒𝚌 𝚋𝚕𝚞𝚎𝚜 

Nobody told me about how you would feel after a Paralympic Games. My first being when I was only 24 and just over 5 years after my life changing accident. I had no idea of all the crazy emotions that would come before, during and after the games. 

Only very few people in the world actually become a Paralympian and experience the crazy village bubble and all highs and lows of the sport. Nothing can really prepare you for how you will feel about it all. 

With the 3 games I’ve been to, the emotions before and during have pretty much been the same, excitement, nerves, determination to succeed. During I had two different experiences whether I’ve been in a team sport or individual. Being with a team is unreal, you have each other to bounce off, talk to, share the training, village life, apartments, down time, exploring, everything with and it’s so much fun. Then you have the games when they begin, there’s highs when you win, frustrations, confusion when you lose. But you have each other.

Winning Gold was unreal, a momentous achievement, creating history and bonds with 11 people that will be memories forever, that only we shared with all our staff too. 

In my previous two games it was ended with disappointment and even though that was tough, I was happy to be home, in home comforts with my family. There were adjustments in the weeks after returning home and I felt unsettled for a little while. 

Winning Gold seems to have exacerbated these crazy emotions more, feeling lost, guilty I’m not doing more now even though media commitments have been non stop and celebrations. Feeling torn you should be training for the next thing but also knowing your body needs rest. 
Battling with yourself, feeling confused as to why?! 😂
But also missing the team, the bubble and the ultimate high of winning. 

Winning a Paralympic Gold is the pinnacle of a para athletes career, I’ve achieved my dream, everything I’ve ever wanted but there’s still some confusion and self doubt there now as to where I can go from here. 

It will ease and get easier, I know this and oh I am so, so proud of myself 🤍

node.text:
Joy in the rain!🥇 ⁣
⁣
Lisbeli Vera Andrade (@lisbelyvera ) 🇻🇪 had the perfect answer to the school bullies who used to make her life a misery at school in Venezuela because she was born without part of her left arm.⁣ 

Lisbeli won 100m and 200m T47 gold at #Tokyo2020. 🥇 🥇 
⁣
“When I crossed the finish line I didn't realise I'd won and I didn’t know how to express my feelings in the moment. I trusted myself to win the race.”⁣
⁣
“When I was at school I was teased because I was missing that part of my body, and that always made me feel different. I would lock myself in my house and say I didn't want to go out.⁣
⁣
“Those jokes made me mature because I knew that at some point I was going to have to face life, that I wasn't always going to be protected and that I had to stand up for myself."⁣
⁣
More on this via our Stories. 
⁣
(Descriptions: It is night, and raining. Lisbeli jumps up on the track, celebrating wildly. Her hair is long and mid-jump it swooshes into the sky. Third picture is Brittani Mason side by side racing with Lisbeli. The final shot is Lisbeli taking in the moment.)⁣
⁣
#Paralympics #Tokyo2020 #ParaAthletics #Venezuela ⁣
⁣
📸: James Varghese Photography.
